        "trailText":"<p><strong>Hannah Slapper:</strong> There's a parallel between bearing the burden of this name and its Yiddish origin. But really, it could have been so much worse</p>",
        "headline":"Yes, I am a Slapper. And I'm proud of it",
        "body":"<p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/garyslapper/status/374940323115327488\" title=\"\">'Can somebody just put me out of my misery and tell me if this is a made-up name,</a>\" tweeted Guardian columnist Zoe Williams, after an <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/03/40-days-of-dating-date-a-friend\" title=\"\">article on dating</a> I wrote last week. Suzanne Moore, more charitably, though possibly sarcastically,  said I had a \"<a href=\"https://twitter.com/suzanne_moore/status/374923115706339328\" title=\"\">dream byline</a>\". As a young writer trying to scramble into some kind of recognition, appearing on Comment is free should have been a thrilling experience. However, a significant chunk of the online conversation I had sparked was about my name.</p><p>Yes, I am a Slapper. And after nearly 25 years of being one, I have to admit that I love it, even though it does get me into trouble every now and then. I am of course talking about my surname, and not my lifestyle. If you're wondering where Slapper comes from, it's not entirely clear. I've delved into it, but my grandparents reckon it was a classic case of immigration misspelling. My great great grandfather moved to Britain from mainland Europe in the early 20th century. We speculate that the original name was something like <em>Schleperovski</em> – from the Yiddish word \"<em>schlepper</em>\" – a person who carries something laboriously. People still use the word \"schlep\" in that context, to haul something with difficulty.</p><p>My grandmother was pretty lucky. She says that up until about 30 years ago people would only poke very gentle fun at the fact it sounded like \"slap her\". Apparently neither of my grandparents realised that the definition had shifted until they heard <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil_Mitchell\" title=\"\">Phil Mitchell</a> use it on an episode of EastEnders. I imagine them sitting there, devastated that our family name was being used to describe, as the Collins dictionary delicately puts it, \"a promiscuous woman\". I can't help but laugh at our misfortune.</p><p>You can just about get away with a name like this if you're male, but unfortunately fate gifted my parents with three daughters. There were some awkward conversations growing up. I remember a particular occasion when, in a crowded restaurant, my father boomed: \"Be proud to be Slappers. you are all Slappers and that is a wonderful and unique thing.\" Not a single head remained unturned.</p><p>In the style of an 80s sitcom protagonist, when introducing myself I often use the catchphrase \"by name, and not by nature!\", with added jazz hands to dispel the awkwardness. Most people  crease up laughing when they hear it. Any semblance of professionalism is immediately abandoned when speaking to bank cashiers, hairdressers, shopkeepers, waiters, publicity teams. The worst is when people actually strain&nbsp;not to laugh, and you worry they'll burst a blood vessel.</p><p>We've all had issues with it. A frazzled teacher threw my sister out of school for wearing a hoody with SLAPPER emblazoned on the back. I also remember baffling a series of substitute teachers who thought I was messing around when I signed the register. My sisters and I have a pretty impressive list of undeserved name-related school punishments. Emails we send are sometimes reported as offensive spam.</p><p>More positively, being a Slapper definitely does make me stand out from the crowd. I've heard from previous bosses that my CV \"popped\" due to the ridiculousness of my name. People remember me more easily, so it's great for building contacts. Unfortunately being taken seriously is another matter entirely.</p><p>When I feel down about it, I try to remember people who are less fortunate than me. American baseball player <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rusty_Kuntz\" title=\"\">Rusty Kuntz</a>, for instance, and all the Ben Dovers and Mike Hunts in the world&nbsp;(and let's not forget Jeremy …). There's also Misty Hyman and the Dicks,&nbsp;Cocks, Shitzers, Boners, and something-bottoms who will join me in simultaneously lamenting and yet celebrating our monikers.</p><p>So here is my declaration to the doubters: I am a Slapper, and I am proud. If you're still not convinced, just&nbsp;be thankful that my mother abandoned her plans to name me Fanny.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/417404497|2013-09-17T11:10:03Z|b73b995063b7ab08b1b4bb0a468535e321dfd878 -->",
