        "trailText":"<strong>Sam Wollaston:</strong> Channel 4's fly-on-the-wall documentary is brilliant – it tells us all about who we are in Britain today",
        "headline":"The Fried Chicken Shop – TV review",
        "body":"<p>One of my favourite London restaurants is Roosters Spot on Clapham High Street. Not sure about the name (something of chickenpox about it, no?) Not sure about the food either to be honest, I've never actually eaten there. I've just looked in once before, when it was the setting for a one-off Cutting Edge film earlier in the year. I liked it then though; other people must have too, because they've come back and we're being served up three more portions of <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-fried-chicken-shop\" title=\"\"><strong>The Fried Chicken Shop</strong></a> (Channel 4)</p><p>It's less about the chicken, more about the people of course, both sides of the counter. Like lovely, sweet Imran who's worked there for two years and likes it when the customers behave badly, \"throwing chicken to each other, chips to each other, ketchup. It's very good when the people are doing this<strong> </strong>...\"</p><p>And Imran's best friend Harris, also from Pakistan, also charming. It hasn't worked out exactly the way Harris's mother planned; she wanted him to be a commercial pilot. Yeah, well, flying, frying, what's the difference? And Harris plans to open his own restaurant, an Italian one. Because, it emerges later, he very much likes – loves in fact, and plans to marry – a beautiful Italian waitress called Faviola. All that remains to do is to tell her.</p><p>There's extra love all over Roosters Spot today. Lovey-dovey customers Leah and Tyrone are in love. \"Aren't we?\" \"Yeah.\" \"Love you too.\" They've got plans for roosts and broods of their own, even though they only look about 15 to me. A word of advice: there's plenty of time for that … oops, too late, number one's on its way. Maybe it's something in the chilli sauce.</p><p>CeeCee's been less lucky in love lately. It's been a while, five months, she tells her best mate Lulu. Fast food is frowned on in their \"Arabic kind of homes,\" says Lulu (drinking too, I imagine, which they've been doing all afternoon). But they just love the chicken, everyone does. And next time they're in, CeeCee has got someone in her life again! I'm telling you, this place sorts you out. If you're single and you're in the south London area, you need to get down to Roosters Spot. Well,&nbsp;I am. It may not be the best place to go for an actual date though, because, as someone here says, fried chicken is \"mad unflattering to eat\".</p><p>\"Ah, Indian birds man,\" a posh boy says to his posh friend, eyeing up a group of Asian girls. \"Any day of the week.\" I think they're posh boys. It's hard to tell these days, even in Kingston Upon Bloody Thames they sound like they come from Kingston Jamaica. These ones look posh though, the hair's usually a giveaway.</p><p>One of them is having trouble with the chilli sauce. \"It feels like I'm having a baby, One Born Every Minute,\" he says. And then they too are discussing when they going to settle down and have babies of their own. It's definitely the sauce. Indian-bird-any-day-of-the-week man wants to end up with a nice little four-bed detached place in Suffolk. Maybe he'll keep chickens of his own.</p><p>Last time round I was uncertain about the location of The Fried Chicken Shop. Clapham's too smart, I&nbsp;was thinking. But it's good to have the&nbsp;posh boys (there are other more annoying ones later), for twattery and range. Actually it's perfect, about as wide a spectrum of society as you'll find anywhere. In Clapham, everyone eats&nbsp;chicken – school kids and students, recording artists and buskers,&nbsp;clubbers, shoppers, drinkers, chancers, dancers, jokers, stockbrokers. And Jessie, a 60-year-old cross-dresser in a tiny lime-green miniskirt that doesn't go low enough to cover her pants or high enough to cover her builder's crack. More like a belt than a skirt. And&nbsp;she moans about&nbsp;what other people are wearing!</p><p>It can't have cost very much to make&nbsp;– rigging up a few fixed cameras&nbsp;in a fast-food place, then leaving them to roll for three weeks. Followed by the mother of all editing jobs, to turn it&nbsp;into something, with stories. (I'd like&nbsp;to know a bit more about the making of it actually, like at&nbsp;what point did people know they were being filmed, and how they got&nbsp;consent etc.)</p><p>Anyway, the result is brilliant – not&nbsp;really about what we eat, but about&nbsp;who we are in Britain today. Well, in London certainly. Who we are,&nbsp;the language we use (mad, spicy&nbsp;language mostly, innit), and what&nbsp;we use that language to talk about. Love, mostly.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/417418949|2013-09-17T11:10:03Z|291baddc488d96e3bb925933f74308f7bdf76f12 -->",
